2921,"Avellán, T., et al.",2017,Considering Resources beyond Water: Irrigation and Drainage Management in the Context of the Water-Energy-Food Nexus. ,Academic-peer reviewed,,Global,,,,,2,7,-1: Constraining,-1,Negative,"Competition for soil and water for the production of food versus energy is an issue and will only increase in the near future, as about 60% more food will need to be produced by 2050 and energy demand is projected to grow by nearly one-third between 2013 and 2040",,see column 14,,,Strong,"total global water withdrawals for food crop irrigation are projected to increase about 10% by 2050 (FAO, 2011a), and water withdrawals for energy production, which currently account for 15% of the world’s total, are expected to increase by 20% by 2035. While water is used for agricultural production, forestry and fishery, utilization also to produce or transport energy in different forms, and the supply chain, consumes about 30% of total energy consumed globally (FAO, 2014). Biofuels offer an alternative energy source to fossil fuels. Their water-related impacts mainly depend on whether they are produced from rainfed or irrigated feedstock crops (Babel et al., 2011). The water requirements of biofuels produced from irrigated crops can be much larger than for fossil fuel resources and can therefore have important implications for local water availability (Gheewala et al., 2014), whereas rainfed production does not substantially alter the water cycle ",,,,14
